<h3>Distance in a coordinate system</h3>
<p><b>Distance in a 2D coordinate plane:</b></p>
<p>The distance between two points on a 2D coordinate plane can be found us=
ing the following distance formula</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;">d =3D =E2=88=9A<span style=3D"border-top: 1=
px solid;padding-top:3px;">(x<sub>2</sub> - x<sub>1</sub>)<sup>2</sup> + (y=
<sub>2</sub> - y<sub>1</sub>)<sup>2</sup></span></p>
<p>where (x<sub>1</sub>, y<sub>1</sub>) and (x<sub>2</sub>, y<sub>2</sub>) =
are the coordinates of the two points involved. The order of the points doe=
s not matter for the formula as long as the points chosen are consistent. F=
or example, given the two points (1, 5) and (3, 2), either 3 or 1 could be =
designated as x<sub>1</sub> or x<sub>2</sub> as long as the corresponding y=
-values are used:</p>
<p>Using (1, 5) as (x<sub>1</sub>, y<sub>1</sub>) and (3, 2) as (x<sub>2</s=
ub>, y<sub>2</sub>):</p>
<table align=3D"center">
	<tbody><tr><td>d =3D</td><td>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"border-top: 1px solid=
;padding-top:3px;">(3 - 1)<sup>2</sup> + (2 - 5)<sup>2</sup></span></td></t=
r>
	<tr><td align=3D"right">=3D</td><td>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"border-top: 1p=
x solid;padding-top:3px;">2<sup>2</sup> + (-3)<sup>2</sup></span></td></tr>
	<tr><td align=3D"right">=3D</td><td>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decoratio=
n:overline;">4 + 9</span></td></tr>
	<tr><td align=3D"right">=3D</td><td>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decoratio=
n:overline;">13</span></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
<p>Using (3, 2) as (x<sub>1</sub>, y<sub>1</sub>) and (1, 5) as (x<sub>2</s=
ub>, y<sub>2</sub>):</p>
<table align=3D"center">
	<tbody><tr><td>d =3D</td><td>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"border-top: 1px solid=
;padding-top:3px;">(1 - 3)<sup>2</sup> + (5 - 2)<sup>2</sup></span></td></t=
r>
	<tr><td align=3D"right">=3D</td><td>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"border-top: 1p=
x solid;padding-top:3px;">(-2)<sup>2</sup> + 3<sup>2</sup></span></td></tr>
	<tr><td align=3D"right">=3D</td><td>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decoratio=
n:overline;">4 + 9</span></td></tr>
	<tr><td align=3D"right">=3D</td><td>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decoratio=
n:overline;">13</span></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
<p>In either case, the result is the same.</p>
<p><b>Distance in a 3D coordinate space:</b></p>
<p>The distance between two points on a 3D coordinate plane can be found us=
ing the following distance formula</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;">d =3D =E2=88=9A<span style=3D"border-top: 1=
px solid;padding-top:3px;">(x<sub>2</sub> - x<sub>1</sub>)<sup>2</sup> + (y=
<sub>2</sub> - y<sub>1</sub>)<sup>2</sup> + (z<sub>2</sub> - z<sub>1</sub>)=
<sup>2</sup></span></p>
<p>where (x<sub>1</sub>, y<sub>1</sub>, z<sub>1</sub>) and (x<sub>2</sub>, =
y<sub>2</sub>, z<sub>2</sub>) are the 3D coordinates of the two points invo=
lved. Like the 2D version of the formula, it does not matter which of two p=
oints is designated (x<sub>1</sub>, y<sub>1</sub>, z<sub>1</sub>) or (x<sub=
>2</sub>, y<sub>2</sub>, z<sub>2</sub>), as long as the corresponding point=
s are used in the formula. Given the two points (1, 3, 7) and (2, 4, 8), th=
e distance between the points can be found as follows:</p>
<table align=3D"center">
	<tbody><tr><td>d =3D</td><td>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"border-top: 1px solid=
;padding-top:3px;">(2 - 1)<sup>2</sup> + (4 - 3)<sup>2</sup> + (8 - 7)<sup>=
2</sup></span></td></tr>
	<tr><td align=3D"right">=3D</td><td>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"border-top: 1p=
x solid;padding-top:3px;">1<sup>2</sup> + 1<sup>2</sup> + 1<sup>2</sup></sp=
an></td></tr>
	<tr><td align=3D"right">=3D</td><td>=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decoratio=
n:overline;">3</span></td></tr>
</tbody></table>

<h3>Distance between two points on Earth's surface</h3>
<p>There are a number of ways to find the distance between two points along=
 the Earth's surface. The following are two common formulas.</p>

<p><b>Haversine formula:</b></p>
<p>The haversine formula can be used to find the distance between two point=
s on a sphere given their latitude and longitude:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://d26tpo4cm8sb6k.cloudfro=
nt.net/img/distance/haversine-formula.png" width=3D"415" height=3D"59" alt=
=3D"haversine formula" class=3D"scaleimg"></p>
<p>In the haversine formula, d is the distance between two points along a g=
reat circle, r is the radius of the sphere, =CF=95<sub>1</sub> and =CF=95<s=
ub>2</sub> are the latitudes of the two points, and =CE=BB<sub>1</sub> and =
=CE=BB<sub>2</sub> are the longitudes of the two points, all in radians.</p=
>
<p>The haversine formula works by finding the great-circle distance between=
 points of latitude and longitude on a sphere, which can be used to approxi=
mate distance on the Earth (since it is mostly spherical). A great circle (=
also orthodrome) of a sphere is the largest circle that can be drawn on any=
 given sphere. It is formed by the intersection of a plane and the sphere t=
hrough the center point of the sphere. The great-circle distance is the sho=
rtest distance between two points along the surface of a sphere.</p>
<p>Results using the haversine formula may have an error of up to 0.5% beca=
use the Earth is not a perfect sphere, but an ellipsoid with a radius of 6,=
378 km (3,963 mi) at the equator and a radius of 6,357 km (3,950 mi) at a p=
ole.  Because of this, Lambert's formula (an ellipsoidal-surface formula), =
more precisely approximates the surface of the Earth than the haversine for=
mula (a spherical-surface formula) can.</p>

<p><b>Lambert's formula:</b></p>
<p>Lambert's formula (the formula used by the calculators above) is the met=
hod used to calculate the shortest distance along the surface of an ellipso=
id. When used to approximate the Earth and calculate the distance on the Ea=
rth surface, it has an accuracy on the order of 10 meters over thousands of=
 kilometers, which is more precise than the haversine formula.</p>
<p>Lambert's formula is as follows:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://d26tpo4cm8sb6k.cloudfro=
nt.net/img/distance/lambert-formula.png" width=3D"136" height=3D"34" alt=3D=
"lambert formula" class=3D"scaleimg"></p>
<p>where a is the equatorial radius of the ellipsoid (in this case the Eart=
h), =CF=83 is the central angle in radians between the points of latitude a=
nd longitude (found using a method such as the haversine formula), f is the=
 flattening of the Earth, and X and Y are expanded below.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://d26tpo4cm8sb6k.cloudfro=
nt.net/img/distance/x-y-value.png" width=3D"214" height=3D"114" alt=3D"x,y =
of lambert formula" class=3D"scaleimg"></p>
<p>Where P =3D (=CE=B2<sub>1</sub> + =CE=B2<sub>2</sub>)/2 and Q =3D (=CE=
=B2<sub>2</sub> - =CE=B2<sub>1</sub>)/2</p>
<p>In the expressions above, =CE=B2<sub>1</sub> and =CE=B2<sub>1</sub> are =
reduced latitudes using the equation below:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;">tan(=CE=B2) =3D (1 - f)tan(=CF=95)</p>
<p>where =CF=95 is the latitude of a point.</p>
<p>Note that neither the haversine formula nor Lambert's formula provides a=
n exact distance because it is not possible to account for every irregulari=
ty on the surface of the Earth.</p>


